article.description: Monica Wright scored a career-high 39 points and Paulisha Kellum made a short jumper with 2.3 seconds left to lift Virginia to a 70-68 win over Boston College on Thursday night.

related.description: Senator-elect Scott Brown returned from Washington and came to watch his daughter, Ayla, play for Boston College's basketball team against Virginia.
related.linkText: U.S. Senator-elect Brown attends BC game
related.title: U.S. Senator-elect Scott Brown watches daughter play for Boston College
related.headline: Senator-elect watches daughter play

article.headline: Kellum's jumper, Wright's 39 too much for Boston College
article.linkText: Kellum's jumper powers No. 22 Virginia by BC
article.story:
BOSTON -- Monica Wright scored a career-high 39 points and Paulisha Kellum made a short jumper with 2.3 seconds left to lift Virginia (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 25 AP) to a 70-68 win over Boston College on Thursday night.

Wright scored 25 points in the second half for the Cavaliers (13-5, 2-2 Atlantic Coast Conference).

Mickel Picco and Brittany Johnson led the Eagles (11-8, 2-2) with 13 points apiece.

Virginia trailed 65-62 with 2 1/2 minutes left, but went up 68-66 when Wright hit a pair of free throws with 35.5 seconds left. Johnson then scored on a drive with 15.7 seconds remaining before Kellum hit the winner.

Massachusetts Senator-elect Scott Brown sat about 15 rows behind the Boston College bench to watch his daughter, Ayla, play for the Eagles.

A reserve, she scored all nine of her points in the final 12:52, including a key 3-pointer that put BC ahead 58-54 with just under 7 1/2 minutes to play.
